## Routing

**Canonical routes live in `{{DOMAIN}}/retrieval.yaml`.** Skills MUST read it first.

Heuristic fall-backs (only when `retrieval.yaml` has no matching pattern):

| Task pattern | Auto-load |
|--------------|-----------|
| "How does X happen end-to-end" | `kind: flow` matching X |
| "Why did we choose X" | `kind: decision` matching X |
| "How do I deploy/rollback/debug X" | `kind: sop` matching X |
| Reviewing system architecture | `kind in (decision, flow, sop)` for the component |
| Designing new feature | `kind in (decision, framework)` for adjacent systems |

When a query recurs without a `retrieval.yaml` match, add the pattern (batched via `/wiki-routes-review`).

## Conventions

- Tag prefix: `{{TAG_PREFIX}}*`
- Reference repo code by path (`<repo-root>/<path>`) — never paste
- Customer- or domain-specific terminology is fine on pages but should be tagged `{{TAG_PREFIX}}<area>/<name>` so future cleanup is easy

## Page Frontmatter (L3-extended)

Pages extend the base schema with two decay-tracker fields per source:

```yaml
---
type: wiki-page
wiki: {{DOMAIN}}
kind: {{KINDS_PIPE}}
sources:
  - path: <repo-root>/<file>
    cited_region: "<whole-file>"               # heading, function name, or "<whole-file>"
    content_hash: <sha256-of-region-text>      # set by /wiki-ingest, checked by /wiki-lint
Updated: YYYY-MM-DD
tags:
---
```

Backward-compat: pages without `cited_region`/`content_hash` keep working. Lint skips the decay check on them.

## Page Filter (L2)

A page exists ONLY if it justifies itself on at least one of:

- **Gotcha** — an edge case or footgun not visible from reading the code
- **Invariant** — what must stay true across changes
- **Why-non-obvious** — rationale behind a choice that isn't derivable from the code
- **Observed failure mode** — production incident, debugging trace, scaling limit

If a page can't justify itself in ~150 words on at least one axis, it restates source — delete it.

## Anti-Patterns

- Pages that restate code ("Component X has methods Y, Z" — grep the code)
- Pasting full configs / compose files
- Tutorials (those belong in the repo README)
- Pages that fail the L2 filter above
